---
description: Server Components in Next.js 15 (App Router). Apply when writing async page/layout/component files that fetch data directly.
globs: "**/app/**/*.tsx"
alwaysApply: false
---

## Context

- Next.js 15 + React 19: Server Components run exclusively on the server — never shipped to the client.
- Server Components can call Prisma, `fs`, third-party SDKs, or any Node.js API directly inside the component body.
- ⚠️ In this project, most DB access goes through the `api/` ExpressJS service via HTTP. Only use Prisma directly in Server Components for admin-internal reads where latency matters and bypassing the API is intentional.

## Usage

```tsx
// app/dashboard/users/page.tsx — async = Server Component
export default async function UsersPage() {
    const users = await prisma.user.findMany({
        select: { id: true, name: true, email: true },
        take: 50,
        orderBy: { createdAt: "desc" },
    });

    return (
        <div>
            {users.map((user) => (
                <p key={user.id}>{user.name}</p>
            ))}
        </div>
    );
}
```

## Available Next.js server utilities

```tsx
import { redirect } from "next/navigation";
import { notFound } from "next/navigation";
import { cookies } from "next/headers";
import { headers } from "next/headers";

redirect("/login");     // Redirect
notFound();             // Show not-found.tsx
cookies().get("token"); // Read cookies (server-only)
```

## Rules

1. Server Components are always `async`
2. Server Components **cannot** use hooks (`useState`, `useEffect`, etc.)
3. Server Components **cannot** access `document` or `window`
4. Add `"use client"` only when interactivity is needed — default to Server Component
5. Never import server-only code in Client Components — use `server-only` package to guard
6. Pass data from Server → Client as props, not via shared state
